title: For Sale:  AR-15 9mm with Glock Dedicated Lower, brand new!
postcontent: One of the problems with adapting the AR platform to 9mm has always been the magazines. The blocks are clunky and the bolts and hammers did not always play well together. This build eliminates several of the most common points of failure by using a billed dedicated lower and an upper made specifically for the 9mm with a Hybrid bolt and top shelf trigger system!The 10.5" barrel is an FN cold forged unit, with a KAK flash can partially recessed into the slant cut 10" guard. The bolt is a G9 hybrid bolt that will work reliably with Glock and Colt magazines. The buffer is a Kaw Valley one piece unit for enhanced reliability and no buffer rattle. The Lower is a Thor unit that is Glock dedicated and will accept pistol, 33 and drum mags with no problems. The trigger system is a Geiselle tuned ALG NibX coated unit for the perfect balance between trigger feel and reliability.The overall result is a great SMG length pistol that is ideal for home defense, SHTF and patrol use owing to the simple fact that if you run a Glock pistol you have ammunition and magazine interchangeability. It will even run fine with .40 and .357 Sig magazines should you ever need to scrounge around. It was a fun project but I am on to the next one. Built from all American made products by a vet with dozens of builds and the positive reviews to back them up.F2F with VA resident non-felons within about 45 minutes of Charlottesville. Not interested in trades at this time unless they are strongly in my favor. ;)

postcontent:
The PF-9 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the 9mm Luger cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-11 and P-3AT pistols with maximum concealability in mind. The PF-9 has a single stack magazine holding 7 rounds. It is one of the lightest and flattest 9 mm ever made. Firing mechanism is Double-Action Only with an automatic hammer block safety.
The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.
The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.

title: For Sale:  KIMBER OF OREGON MATCH RIFLE
location: N. E. of Nashville, Nashville, Tennessee
postcontent: This is a Kimber Model 82 Government match rifle, made in the original Clackamas Oregon plant. Brand new in factory carton, mint condition, unfired, all parts, manual, range test results, etc., still in sealed pouches. Front sight inserts in cosmolined pouch.The US military has long used rimfire caliber rifles for basic marksmanship training as well as JROTC/ROTC/CAP/CMP programs. These rifles are among some of the best you can get, are rare, and are widely sought after by both collectors and target shooters alike.Produced for the US Army from 1987-1990, Kimber of Oregon contracted these single-shot rifles. This is a single shot .22 LR (only) heavy target rifle than has a 25" free floating barrel, an overall weight of 10.75 lbs., a length of 43 inches, an adjustable trigger, three butt plate spacers and a hand stop assembly. They were issued with a very precise Kimber rear aperture sight, a front sight with ten inserts, and are renowned for their accuracy. Accuracy results showed the Kimber test rifle capable of staying well within the 10ring of the 50-yd. and 50-meter targets used in conventional small-bore competition with standard ammunition.For whatever reason, the Army chose to keep them in arsenal storage for more than a decade and not use them. Most were passed on to the Civilian Marksmanship Program (CMP) a non-profit based at Camp Perry, Ohio, for disposal to pre-qualified civilian shooters. As soon as they hit the CMP's shelves, they rapidly sold out. Kimber 82 Government models are excellent shooters and are extremely collectable. A quick search of Gunbroker shows these rifles garnering prices of up to $1600. You would be hard-pressed to find a comparable match rifle for this price and this gun would round any serious Kimber oficiandos collection.Asking $1175- CASH ONLY, NON-NEGOTIABLE NO TRADES.YOU MUST BE A TN RESIDENT – NON FELON, NO EXCEPTIONS.
